    <div class="content-container">
      <article>
        <h2><i class="fas fa-balance-scale"></i> YouTube Thumbnail Comparator (A/B Test)</h2>
        <p>Choosing the right thumbnail can be the difference between 1,000 views and 100,000 views. Top creators like MrBeast spend thousands of dollars testing multiple thumbnails. <strong>Xizoa Hub's Thumbnail Comparator</strong> lets you do the same for free.</p>
        <p>By comparing two versions of your thumbnail side-by-side or using our interactive slider, you can spot small details like color contrast, text readability, and facial expressions that might affect your Click-Through Rate (CTR).</p>

        <h3><i class="fas fa-eye"></i> How to Choose the Winner?</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Contrast:</strong> Which one pops out more against the dark/white background?</li>
            <li><strong>Readability:</strong> Can you read the text instantly? (The "Glance Test").</li>
            <li><strong>Focal Point:</strong> Where do your eyes go first? It should be the main subject or emotion.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3><i class="fas fa-laptop-code"></i> Tool Features</h3>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Side-by-Side View:</strong> Standard comparison to see how they look next to each other on a search page.</li>
            <li><strong>Slider View:</strong> Drag a slider over the images to compare specific changes (like font color or background saturation).</li>
            <li><strong>Privacy First:</strong> Your images are processed in your browser. We do not upload or store your thumbnails.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2><i class="fas fa-question-circle"></i> Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        
        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What makes a thumbnail clickable?</h3>
            <p>Bright colors, high contrast, clear text (less than 5 words), and a strong emotional expression on the face usually drive higher clicks.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Should I use red arrows and circles?</h3>
            <p>Yes, but don't overdo it. Red circles direct the viewer's eye to the most important part of the image, creating curiosity.</p>
        </div>

